# Methodology

In this project, we are primarily making use of Google Cloud functions to set up an information streaming pipeline to Extract, Transform and Load data from Google Cloud Storage to Google BigQuery. Such a setup can be quite helpful in settings where a large amount of data has to be processed as soon as they are loaded into a cloud storage bucket. In this system, we created a cloud function with an event trigger. This event trigger is a ‘Cloud Storage’ type trigger, which has been set up for creating/finalizing files in the specified bucket. By default, we are setting 256 MB for each instance of this cloud function. This setting can be further modified to accommodate more extensive processing or event monitoring needs (Scalability). After being successfully deployed, a given cloud function can have multiple instances handling several requests. On the other side, we have set up a dataset within BigQuery, in which we have created tables with the appropriate schema. The dataset and table names must be specified in the cloud function code. We also have to define an entry point while setting up the cloud function. This entry point defines the method that will be read at code’s execution [2].

Once the function was deployed, it was tested through the Google Cloud Console platform. After testing, the files from the dataset “Amazon Book Reviews” were uploaded to the specified bucket in Google Cloud Storage. This dataset consists of two files, namely ‘books_data.csv’ and ‘Books_rating.csv’. The former is of size 181 MB, while the latter is of size 2.86 GB. In total, we aim to process this 2.87 GB of data collectively. Once the files have been uploaded, we can test the status of the result through Logs, available in the Google Cloud Functions console. The log explorer is a valuable part of the Google Cloud Console to explore in depth the results returned by the deployed cloud functions, including errors, bugs, and crashes. As soon as the files are uploaded, function execution starts, and the code looks out for the creation of both files (in the specified bucket). In cases where one file is missing, that is, not uploaded, the function captures the error, which can be seen in the logs by the user. Furthermore, when we upload two files, data from both files are streamed/imported to respective tables in BigQuery. Thus, the designed cloud function is capable of handling multiple requests at the same time.

The data is thus streamed from the bucket in Cloud Storage to BigQuery, where we can further process and analyze data.

## Scalability in our ETL Pipeline

It is pertinent to understand what exactly we mean by scalability for a distributed system. A distributed system is scalable when it can handle an increasing workload in a dynamic setting [1]. One way to achieve this is by increasing the resources for a given system. Almost every component of the Google Cloud Platform has extensive scalability features. In particular, we can easily scale when it comes to Google Cloud Functions by adjusting the maximum number of instances of the cloud function the user deploys.

Google Cloud Functions provide the user with two types of cloud functions, namely, 1st generation cloud functions and 2nd generation cloud functions. In our project, we have deployed a 1st Gen Cloud function to stream data from Cloud Storage to BigQuery, with a trigger of type ‘Cloud Storage’ that responds to the event of the ‘creation/finalization’ of files in the specified bucket. While setting up a cloud function, the advanced setting tab ‘Runtime, build, connections and security settings allow us to tweak our system to scale according to our needs. In particular, we allocated 256 MB of memory to our deployed cloud functions and set the maximum number of instances to 3000. This means that at any time, if needed, GCP will deploy up to 3000 instances of our function to handle a heavy workload (3000 requests). The 1st Generation cloud functions can have a maximum of 3000 instances, where each can only handle one request. So to scale or to handle more requests, the cloud function provides us with the option to have multiple instances of our cloud function. This is referred to as automatic scaling or ‘auto-scaling behaviour’ [3]. Here, depending on the volume of requests, Cloud Functions is capable of automatically creating and using new instances [3].

While testing the scalability, we coded our cloud function (in Python 3.7) to respond to two requests. The first is the upload of books_data.csv, and the second is the upload of Books_rating.csv. Upon uploading both files simultaneously, we observed that two instances of our cloud functions were deployed to handle the requests.
![][image1]

[image1]: <data:image/png;base64,>

As observed in the image, the spike in the number of instances to 2 happens when both files are uploaded. Only one instance is deployed when the function is designed to respond to only the uploading of one event. Furthermore, as aforementioned, we can scale up by allocating more memory to our cloud function. With 256 MB memory (1st Gen), GCP provides ‘0.167 vCPU’. For 1st Gen Cloud functions, this can be scaled up to 8192 MB per the system's requirements.

## Concurrency in our ETL Pipeline

By default, Google Cloud Functions does not provide direct concurrency with their First Generation Cloud Functions. Each and every instance of a cloud function will process only one concurrent request at any given time. However, multiple requests to a cloud function at any given time will result in the automatic deployment of multiple instances of that function, where each instance will handle one request. This is how Google Cloud Functions tries to provide concurrency. It has to be noted that the second generation functions can handle concurrency in a more direct manner. It can process up to 1000 concurrent requests per function instance.

For testing, we created a separate cloud function that extracted user reviews for a given book. For the sake of simplicity, we used a static value with the book named “Mere Christianity”. This had an HTTP trigger type, and we enabled unauthenticated invocation so that we can test a high volume of concurrent requests. We set maximum instances to 3000 and kept allocated memory to 256 MB, which is default.

We tested this on 3 different scenarios. First, we tested with 2 parallel requests, for which it was observed that 2 instances of the cloud functions were deployed. This was done using the ‘curl’ command from two separate terminals. Then we tested with 3 parallel requests and observed that 3 instances were deployed. Lastly, we created a separate Python script that concurrently sent 10 requests to the trigger URI. Consequently, through the metric logs, we observed that 10 such instances were deployed to handle those requests. These 3 scenarios can be seen through the image given below, at approximately UTC time 11:24 AM (2 concurrent requests), 11:34 AM (3 concurrent requests), and finally at 11:53 AM (for 10 concurrent requests).

## Result

Scalability and Concurrency for Google Cloud Functions were intensively tested in an empirical manner. It was observed that 3 instances were deployed to load all the data of both files (2.87 GB) in 96.45 seconds when 256 MB of memory was allocated to the function. When the memory was increased to 512 MB, it was observed that 3 instances were used to load both of the files, but with considerably lesser duration. When 1 GB of memory was allocated, it took 2 instances to upload the Books_rating.csv (2.86 GB) in 31.99 seconds and 1 instance was allocated to load books_data.csv (181 MB) in 17.259 seconds. Lastly, when the memory was increased to 4 GB, it took around the same time as the previous case, with 2 instances to load the bigger file and 1 instance to load the smaller one. This can be seen in the figure given below.

For concurrency, as previously mentioned, the cloud function was handling multiple concurrent requests by deploying multiple instances of the function. In our test, we triggered 10 simultaneous requests to extract user reviews for a given title, for which 10 instances of the function were deployed.
